WATER PERF profiling result (gpuTimer + process-of-elimination toggles at a fixed deck bench): the water surface cost ~9ms of a ~20ms deck frame, and it ISOLATES cleanly: NOT vertex count (a coarse separate water mesh GRID 4 vs 9 = 36 vs 121 verts changed nothing), NOT swell VS-ALU (~0.4ms), NOT raster/blend overdraw (~0.5ms) -- it is ~8.4ms of per-pixel FS-ALU spread DIFFUSELY across the water shader (raymarch + 3x seaHeight wave-normal + absorption + Fresnel + tonemap) over a large screen area. No single hotspot: capping the high-freq wave octaves by distance saved ~3.5%, and removing the SSR (a per-pixel matrix mult + 2nd scene-tex tap) saved ~0 (compiler/cache already absorbed it). METHOD that nailed it: a `uWaterFlat` uniform that early-returns a flat colour in the water FS branch -> (full - trivialFS) = FS-ALU, (trivialFS - waterOff) = raster/blend; plus toggling `__waterSurface` off = total water cost. LESSON: when a cost is diffuse per-pixel over a big fill area with no hotspot, the only large lever left is STRUCTURAL -- render the water pass at HALF RESOLUTION to a separate buffer and upsample (4x fewer water FS invocations) -- micro-quants (octaves/SSR/verts) only nibble. Always isolate vert vs raster vs FS-ALU by measurement before cutting; intuition ('half-sample the refraction', 'fewer verts') was wrong here twice.